y relevant in the cultural and theological contexts of the early modern period in general.In treating both canonical and lesser known Donne texts, John Donne's Performances hopes to make a significant contribution not only to Donne criticism and research into early modern culture: by using concepts of performance and performativity as its major theoretical backdrop, it aims to establish an interdisciplinary link with the field of performance studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 4aShakespeare 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aDevotions.  aJ. L. Austin.  aJohn Donne.  aearly modern period.  aerotic poetry.  alinguistic performativity.  apatronage seeking.  aperformance.  asermon.  aspeech act theory.1 aFetzer, Margret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779296940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847792969423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847792969/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles